import React, { useState, useRef } from 'react';
import './DragAndDropKanban.css'; // Import your CSS for styling

const DragAndDropKanban = () => {
  const [columns, setColumns] = useState([
    { id: 'column-1', title: 'To Do' },
    { id: 'column-2', title: 'In Progress' },
    { id: 'column-3', title: 'Done' },
  ]);

  const [items, setItems] = useState([
    { id: 'item-1', name: 'Task 1', columnId: 'column-1' },
    { id: 'item-2', name: 'Task 2', columnId: 'column-2' },
    { id: 'item-3', name: 'Task 3', columnId: 'column-1' },
    { id: 'item-4', name: 'Task 4', columnId: 'column-3' },
  ]);

  const dragItem = (itemId, newColumnId) => {
    setItems(Items =>
      Items.map(item =>
        item.id === itemId ? { ...item, columnId: newColumnId } : item
      )
    );
  };

  return (
    <div className="kanban-board">
      {columns.map(column => (
        <div key={column.id} className="kanban-column">
          <h3>{column.title}</h3>
          <div className="kanban-items">
            {column.id === 'column-1' ? (
              items
                .filter(item => item.columnId === column.id)
                .map(item => (
                  <div
                    key={item.id}
                    className="kanban-item"
                    draggable
                    onDragStart={(e) => {
                      e.dataTransfer.setData('text/plain', item.id);
                    }}
                  >
                    {item.name}
                  </div>
                ))
            ) : (
              items
                .filter(item => item.columnId === column.id)
                .map(item => (
                  <div
                    key={item.id}
                    className="kanban-item"
                    draggable
                    onDragStart={(e) => {
                      e.dataTransfer.setData('text/plain', item.id);
                    }}
                  >
                    {item.name}
                  </div>
                ))
            )}
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  );
};

export default DragAndDropKanban;
```

**Explanation:**

1. **Import Necessary Modules:**
   - `React`: For creating React components.
   - `useState`: To manage the state of the columns and items.
   - `useRef`: (Optional, but good for more complex drag-and-drop)  Useful for potentially tracking drag information, although this example doesn't directly use `useRef`.

2. **`DragAndDropKanban` Component:**
   -  This is your main Kanban board component.

3. **State Variables:**
   - `columns`: An array of column objects, each with an `id` and `title`. This represents the different stages of your Kanban board.
   - `items`: An array of item objects, each with an `id`, `name`, and `columnId`.  `columnId` indicates which column the item belongs to.

4. **`dragItem` Function:**
   - This function is the core logic for handling the drag-and-drop operation.
   - It takes the `itemId` of the item being dragged and the `newColumnId` (the ID of the column it's being dropped onto) as arguments.
   - It updates the `items` state by mapping over the `items` array.  If the item's ID matches the `itemId`, it updates the item's `columnId` with the `newColumnId`.  Otherwise, it keeps the item unchanged.  This ensures that only the dragged item's column ID is updated, while the rest remain the same.

5. **JSX (Rendering)**
   - **`kanban-board` Container:** The outermost `div` element, applied the `kanban-board` class for overall styling.
   - **Mapping Columns:**  `columns.map()` iterates over the `columns` array and creates a `div` element for each column.
     - **Column Title:**  `<h3>{column.title}</h3>` displays the title of the column.
     - **Items Area:** `<div className="kanban-items">` contains the items for the current column.
     - **Conditional Rendering for Items:**  An `if` statement (`column.id === 'column-1' ? ... : ...`) conditionally renders the items for each column.  This is because you want to use different item lists for each column.  This is also where the drag-and-drop logic is implemented.
         - **Filtering Items:** `.filter(item => item.columnId === column.id)` filters the `items` array to include only the items that belong to the current column.
         - **Mapping Items:** `.map(item => ...)` iterates over the filtered items and creates a `div` element for each item.
           - **`draggable` Attribute:** `draggable="true"` makes the `div` element draggable.
           - **`onDragStart` Event Handler:** `onDragStart={(e) => { ... }}` is called when the user starts dragging the item.
             - `e.dataTransfer.setData('text/plain', item.id);` sets the data being dragged.  `'text/plain'` specifies the data type (plain text). The value is the `item.id`, which will be used to identify the item being dragged. This is crucial for the target column to know which item was dragged.
